To contain spread of corona virus and in view of violation of border shut down order by commuters plying Maiduguri-Damaturu road , the joint High Powered Response Team for the Prevention and Control of COVID-19 from Borno and Yobe states have yesterday met to work out mechanism to tighten the major borders of the two states. The committee said over 1,200 travellers intercepted entering Maiduguri from Damatiru have been grouped into categories of repatriation, quarantine and other preventable punishments. The two states COVID-19 committees were led by their chairmen and also deputy governors, Umar Usman kadafur of Borno and Idi Garde Gubana of Yobe respectively. The purpose of the meeting according to the chairmen during their separate remarks is to put heads together and come up with a mechanism that will ensure that their borders are properly closed down for control of COVID 19. The chairmen said the two States have suffered too much loss of lives due to insurgency and could not afford to accommodate any pandemic for now, adding that all efforts must be done to curtail the outbreak of the disease in the area. They lamented that the vehicles that were exempted from the restrictions order are the ones used to convey passengers into the States, but warned their leadership that henceforth anybody found wanting would be prosecuted and punished. The two committees agreed that from the day of the meeting, all their borders would be closed down for two weeks and advised all motorists to abide by the order or face the consequences. The deputy governor of Borno state, Umar Usman Kadafur said: “Within two days, the influx of travelers into the State intercepted are over 1200, but they have been group into categories of repatriation, quarantine and other preventable punishments.” The two chairmen later addressed over 500 travellers intercepted and took them for two weeks quarantine.